column903: Basically  there is one role/color who is ALWAYS going to choose X or Y. It doesn't matter what the next person does because the two highest payments are in that row (either X or Y). For example  in display 7  Green is the only player that has their two highest payouts in one row (in this case  row X). So Green will  ALWAYS choose X_G. Everybody SHOULD base their decision on that one "stable" choice. Red should choose X_R because we know that Green will choose X_G no matter what since he/she will still get a higher payout by choosing X over Y (if Green chose Y  then he/she is essentially choosing to get either 14 or 10). Orange will choose Y_O since Red will choose X_R. Finally  Blue will choose X_B since Orange will choose Y_O.

The start depended on which colour you played as but it is described best starting from player 4. Player 4 gives their       answer after the other 3 players have already decided. That means player 4 has the most incentive just to pick which      ever option gives them the higher points because the other player that affects their options has already gone. So every    player before Player 4 must look to see what option Player 4 is most inclined to choose given the answers already          (aside from Player 1 who must look at what their options give Player 4 and then make assumptions as to what effects   that has on Players 4 and then 3 and then 2) and what options that can select. In general  if everyone was willing to not   go after their highest option  all four players could win their second highest. The whole process requires assuming the other players understand this as well.

You just have to back solve what each player is most likely to choose. If you make 1st choice  you can check the expected playout from both your options and see which is higher. If you make the 4th choice  it is very simple to pick the higher number from the column that the 1st choice already made. As long as everybody uses this strategy  everybody is sure to get a high outcome.
I plot the possible scenarios that can happen and then choose the better options (not necessarily the best option out of the 4).

I tried to think win-win. I would start looking at the payoff of orange. And deduce which one orange would pick  then deduce blue's choice  then green  then red. I would try to find a way so that everyone would make a good amount of money  since everyone wants to make money  I knew that I'd have to consider what others might pick.

I pretend I am the first player. I choose X and look at what it will make player four choose  then I see what player three would choose from player four's choice  then see what player two would choose from player three's choice  and see what amount I would end up with from what player two's choice. I then do this with Y and see again what I would end up with. I compare the two amounts and choose the highest number  assuming everyone will play these X's or Y's. I will base any of my choices for any player on this scenario. If I am getting the lower of the two amounts from the player after me  I study the next player's choices and see if there is someone who is not playing the same way. If they are not  I try to see if I can figure out their strategy  then keep playing a number of more games to see if one of the players continues this pattern. If not  I continue to play the same way  but if they kept not playing the same strategy as I was  I would have to figure another way of approaching the game as to insure I got the safest  highest scores consitently.

if you are not the first person to choose  you can easily deduce from the previous choice that which of your decision is better. if you are the first person  you can make two assumption in order to predict the results

I always assume other players would make the choice which maximized the amount they would get out of each match. I would see what each player would choose based on that  and make my choice from there.

I tried to pick out the larger numbers in order to receive more tokens. But  I also had to think about how the other player would do that too and how that could affect what I receive. So  I would try to pick out the number that's higher in comparison to the color next to me as well  so in case the other player picked out a bigger number I'd know which one to expect.

The best way for me to calculate my maximum payoff is to estimate what the next player will do by looking at the payoffs possible for the next player. He/she is most likely to choose the option that maximizes his/her own payoff  so I made my decision based upon the supposed 'greed' of the next player

I would first look at what I thought the subsequent player would choose  then I made my decision based on how their actions could best work to my advantage (even if this meant that I would not receive the highest ammount possible).
